linkTarget.anchoringText: The reservoir consists of fluvio-deltaic sands that were deposited along a SW-NE direction While, the reservoir package is correlatable as a whole, individual sands seen in wells cannot be correlated across the field due to the inherent heterogeneity in a fluvial reservoir. While individual sand bodies are discontinuous, lateral continuity is established by amalgamation of these sand bodies. A discontinuous shale layer subdivides the reservoir package in to the upper and lower sand zones (Figure 1). This shale is not seen at all the wells, and is likely to be a result of subsequent erosion by channel bodies rather than non-deposition. These gaps in the shale layer allow vertical communication across the reservoir.

linkTarget.anchoringText: Analysis of the facies proportions seen at the wells showed areas with high proportion of channel sands. These wells were grouped into ‘fairways’ oriented along the regional depositional trend (Figure 5, red dotted lines indicate fairways). Wells that lie within the geologically determined ‘fairways’ coincide with the well-connected wells identified from the RTA analysis. This gave us more confidence in the concept of ‘fairways’ and a clearer understanding of the preferential movement of water in the reservoir.

linkTarget.anchoringText: Saturation logs and PLTs are crucial for understanding the vertical movement of water. Among the data sets available is a PLT from a recent well and 3 other saturation logs (Figure 7). The flowing PLT data indicated that the bottom most layer produces water even though the zones above produce the maximum oil. The saturation data from other wells (that had broken water) also indicated that water was approaching from the bottom. The lower sand zone is better in terms of properties – thicker with more amalgamation of channels – resulting in more lateral connectivity.

linkTarget.anchoringText: Figure 13 shows the three fairway realizations modelled for the upper sand zone (top figure) and the lower sand zone (bottom figure) that resulted in a good history match on WBT timing. The coloured bands are the fairways while the grey background represents the non-fairway region. The colours have no relevance to the properties of the fairways and have been merely used here to identify the different fairways. Fairways in the lower sand zone are wider and better connected as compared to the upper sand zone (Figure 13). This is evident in the well logs, where thicker channel sands are seen in the lower sand zone, interpreted to be a result of amalgamation of several channels.

Subsequently, these realizations were used to predict fluid recovery and water breakthrough risks in addition to validating the results from analytical studies.
